<TEXT>
<P>
 20th Century Ratings Drop on Earthquake Loss: Standard & Poor's Corp. 
downgraded the financial security ratings of Woodland Hills-based 20th Century 
Insurance Co. and its sister, 21st Century Casualty Co., to the "vulnerable" 
range from the "secure" range, citing the insurers' estimated $600 million in 
losses from the Northridge earthquake. The new ratings are BB ("may be 
adequate" to meet claims obligations), down from BBB+ ("adequate"). Parent 
company 20th Century Industries' credit assessment rating dropped to B from 
BB+, and the firm remains under review for further downgrades, the ratings 
agency said. 20th Century has applied to the state Insurance Department for 
earthquake insurance premium hikes averaging 172% for conventional homes and 
400% for condominiums. 
